# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cloudflare-workers
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare was founded in 2009 by Matthew Prince, Lee Holloway, and Michelle Zatlyn.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] The company went public on the New York Stock Exchange in 2019 under the ticker symbol NET.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare has since expanded its offerings to include edge computing through its Workers platform, a public DNS resolver (1.1.1.1), and a VPN-like service known as WARP.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In recent years, the company has integrated artificial intelligence into its infrastructure, acquiring companies such as Replicate and launching tools to manage AI bots and scrapers.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] According to W3Techs, Cloudflare is used by approximately 21.3% of all websites on the Internet as of January 2026.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] The company has been the subject of controversy regarding its policy of content neutrality.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare has also faced criticism and litigation regarding copyright infringement by websites using its services, notably losing a lawsuit against Japanese publishers in 2025.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] The company experienced significant global outages in late 2025 which disrupted services for major platforms internationally.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare was founded on July 26, 2009, by Matthew Prince, Lee Holloway, and Michelle Zatlyn.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Prince and Holloway had previously collaborated on Project Honey Pot, a product of Unspam Technologies that partly inspired the basis of Cloudflare.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In 2009, the company was venture-capital funded.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] On August 15, 2019, Cloudflare submitted its S-1 filing for an initial public offering on the New York Stock Exchange under the stock ticker NET.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] It opened for public trading on September 13, 2019, at $15 per share.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In 2020, Cloudflare co-founder and COO Michelle Zatlyn was named president.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare has acquired web-services and security companies, including StopTheHacker (February 2014), CryptoSeal (June 2014), Eager Platform Co.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Replicate (November 2025), and Human Native (January 2026).
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Since at least 2017, Cloudflare has used a wall of lava lamps at its San Francisco headquarters as a source of randomness for encryption keys, alongside double pendulums at its London offices and a Geiger counter at its Singapore offices.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] The lava lamp installation implements the Lavarand method, where a camera transforms the unpredictable shapes of the "lava" blobs into a digital image.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In Q4 2022, Cloudflare provided paid services to 162,086 customers.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In October 2024, Cloudflare won a lawsuit against patent troll Sable Networks.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Sable paid Cloudflare $225,000, granted it a royalty-free license to its patent portfolio, and dedicated its patents to the public by abandoning its patent rights.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In November 2025, it was announced Cloudflare had agreed to acquire Replicate, a San Francisco–based platform that enables software developers to run, fine-tune, and deploy open-source machine-learning models via an API without managing infrastructure.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In January 2026, Cloudflare released an analysis regarding BGP routing leaks observed from the Venezuelan state-owned ISP CANTV (AS8048), which occurred on January 2 coincides with the arrest of Nicolás Maduro.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] While some security researchers had speculated that the outages were linked to U.S. cyber operations, Cloudflare's data indicated that the anomalies were consistent with a pattern of "insufficient routing export and import policies" by the ISP rather than malicious external interference.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In January 2026, Cloudflare acquired Human Native, an AI data marketplace that brokers transactions between developers and content creators, for an undisclosed amount.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] On January 16, 2026, Cloudflare acquired The Astro Technology Company, the developers behind the open-source web framework Astro.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In May 2026, Cloudflare announced the elimination of approximately 1,100 positions, around 20 percent of its workforce, in a restructuring the company attributed to the rapid adoption of artificial intelligence tools.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] The announcement coincided with the company's first-quarter 2026 earnings, which reported a record $639.8 million in quarterly revenue, a 34 percent year-over-year increase.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] CEO Matthew Prince stated the cuts were not driven by performance concerns but reflected roles made obsolete by AI, and that Cloudflare expected to employ more people by the end of 2027 than at any point during 2026.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare provides network and security products for consumers and businesses, utilizing edge computing, reverse proxies for web traffic, data center interconnects, and a content distribution network to serve content across its network of servers.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] It supports transport layer protocols TCP, UDP, QUIC, and many application layer protocols such as DNS over HTTPS, SMTP, and HTTP/2 with support for HTTP/2 Server Push.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] As of 2023, Cloudflare handles an average of 45 million HTTP requests per second.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] As of 2024, Cloudflare servers are powered by AMD EPYC 9684X processors.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare also provides analysis and reports on large-scale outages, including Verizon's October 2024 outage.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In April 2026, Cloudflare released an open-source CMS called EmDash, intended to align with serverless and edge-based architecture.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In 2023, Cloudflare launched "Workers AI", a framework allowing for use of Nvidia GPU's within Cloudflare's network.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In 2024, Cloudflare launched a tool that prevents bots from scraping websites.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] To build automatic bot detector models, the company analyzed "AI" bots and crawler traffic.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] The company also launched an "AI" assistant to generate charts based on queries by leveraging "Workers AI".
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare announced plans in September 2024 to launch a marketplace where website owners can sell "AI" model providers access to scrape their site's content.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In March 2025, Cloudflare announced a new feature called "AI Labyrinth", which combats unauthorized "AI" data scraping by serving fake "AI"-generated content to LLM bots.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In July, the company rolled out a permission-based setting to allow websites to automatically block online bots from scraping data and content.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare released AutoRAG into beta in 2025.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] AutoRAG (retrieval augmented generation) creates a vector database of a website's unstructured content to identify relationships between concepts.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] It is part of an initiative with Microsoft, alongside their NLWeb standard, to make websites easier for people and automated systems to query.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare and GoDaddy partnered in April 2026 to enable AI Crawl Control features on GoDaddy hosted websites.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] This would allow site owners to decide how AI bot crawlers interact with their content.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare provides free and paid DDoS mitigation services that protect customers from distributed denial of service (DDoS) attacks.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare received media attention in June 2011 for providing DDoS mitigation for the website of LulzSec, a black hat hacking group.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In March 2013, The Spamhaus Project was targeted by a DDoS attack that Cloudflare reported exceeded 300 gigabits per second (Gbit/s).
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Patrick Gilmore, of Akamai, stated that at the time it was "the largest publicly announced DDoS attack in the history of the Internet".
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] While trying to defend Spamhaus against the DDoS attacks, Cloudflare ended up being attacked as well; Google and other companies eventually came to Spamhaus' defense and helped it to absorb the unprecedented amount of attack traffic.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In 2014, Cloudflare began providing free DDoS mitigation for artists, activists, journalists, and human rights groups under the name "Project Galileo".
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In 2017, it extended the service to electoral infrastructure and political campaigns under the name "Athenian Project".
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] By 2025, more than 2,900 users and organizations were participating in Project Galileo, including 31 US states.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In February 2014, Cloudflare claimed to have mitigated an NTP reflection attack against an unnamed European customer, which it stated peaked at 400 Gbit/s.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In November 2014, it reported a 500 Gbit/s DDoS attack in Hong Kong.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In July 2021, the company claimed to have absorbed a DDoS attack three times larger than any it had previously recorded, which its corporate blog implied was over 1.2 Tbit/s in total.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In February 2023, Cloudflare reported blocking a 71 million request-per-second DDoS attack which "the company says was the largest HTTP DDoS attack on record".
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare blocked the then largest publicly recorded DDoS attack in August 2025, with volumetric attacks peaking at 11.5 terabits per second (tbps).
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] This was surpassed in December 2025 when an Aisuru botnet launched a 31.4 tbps attack, with a requests-per-second rate exceeding 200 million, against multiple companies in the telecommunications sector, a campaign Cloudflare dubbed "The Night Before Christmas".
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In April 2026, Cloudflare released a system designed to let users implement their own custom DDoS mitigation logic, using protocols built on User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In 2017, Cloudflare launched Cloudflare Workers, a serverless computing platform for creating new applications, augmenting existing ones, without configuring or maintaining infrastructure.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] It has expanded to include Workers KV, a low-latency key-value data store; Cron Triggers, for scheduling Cron jobs; and additional tooling for developers to deploy and scale their code across the globe.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In 2020, Cloudflare released a JAMstack platform for developers to deploy websites on Cloudflare's Edge infrastructure, under the name "Pages".
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In 2022, Cloudflare announced an Edge SQL database, D1, which is built on SQLite.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In August 2023, Cloudflare and IBM announced a partnership providing bot management capabilities to protect IBM Cloud customers from malicious bots and automated threats.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] The same month, Cloudflare was hired by SpaceX to boost the performance of Starlink.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In September, the company launched Cloudflare Fonts as a competitor to Google Fonts.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In April 2020, Cloudflare announced it was moving away from using reCAPTCHA in favor of hCaptcha.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In September 2022, Cloudflare began to test Turnstile – an alternative to CAPTCHA.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] The product, instead of presenting a visual CAPTCHA for the user to solve, automatizes the verification process by conducting JavaScript-based checks inside the browser to determine whether the user is a real person or an automated entity.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] The algorithm reportedly uses machine learning to optimize the process.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Through a contract with the Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency, Cloudflare provides registry and authoritative DNS services to the .gov top-level domain.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare also launched Cloudflare for Campaigns in 2020, to offer free cybersecurity tools to political campaigns.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Those tools expanded to include secure email systems in 2025.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In November 2020, Cloudflare announced Cloudflare for Teams, consisting of a DNS resolver and web gateway called "Gateway", and a zero-trust authentication service called "Access".
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare released an Oblivious HTTP relay service in 2022, called Privacy Gateway.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare announced a partnership with PhonePe in January 2023 to secure its mobile payment system.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In February, Cloudflare launched Wildebeest to allow Mastodon users to set up and run their own instances on Cloudflare's infrastructure.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In August 2023, Cloudflare started the Project Cybersafe Schools program as part of a $20 million grant program from Amazon Web Services, making 70 percent of public school districts in the United States eligible for no-cost cybersecurity services.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In March 2024, it announced Firewall for AI to defend applications running large language models (LLMs).
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In September, Cloudflare announced Ephemeral IDs, which identifies fraudulent activity by linking behavior to a client through a short-lived, generated ID, rather than the traditional means of using an IP address.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] The same month, the company also announced all ISP and equipment manufacturers could use its DNS resolvers for free.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare introduced the Cloudforce One threat events platform in March 2025, offering real-time insights into cyberattacks using data gathered from Cloudflare's network.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare's overarching secure access service edge (SASE) platform debuted in October 2020.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare announced the acquisition of Area 1 Security in February 2022, a company who developed a product designed to combat phishing email attacks.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare acquired Nefeli Networks in March 2024, a cloud networking company, co-founded by computer scientist Sylvia Ratnasamy.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In 2019, Cloudflare released a VPN-like service called WARP, and open sourced the custom underlying WireGuard implementation written in Rust.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In January 2021, the company began providing its "Waiting Room" digital queue product for free for COVID-19 vaccination scheduling under the title "Project Fair Shot".
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Project Fair Shot later won a Webby People's Choice Award in 2022 for Event Management under the Apps & Software category.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In March 2023, Cloudflare announced post-quantum cryptography will be made freely and forever available to cloud services, applications and Internet connections.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare released the Speed Brain and Instant Purge features in September 2024, to significantly reduce page load latency by prefetching content, and invalidating cached content in under 150ms.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In 2024, Cloudflare announced plans to launch a new payment method, called Stripe Link, which went into beta in the fall.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Since 2010, Cloudflare has collaborated with the National Center for Missing & Exploited Children to provide data, files, and supplemental investigation from abuse reports observed on its network.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare designed a new NCMEC reporting system in 2024, updating it in 2025 by integrating Cloudflare Workflows and making the CSAM scanning tool accessible globally.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] On June 1, 2012, the hacker group UGNazi compromised some of Cloudflare CEO Matthew Prince's accounts and redirected visitors of the website 4chan to a Twitter account belonging to UGNazi.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] They allegedly used social engineering to trick AT&T support staff into giving them access to Prince's voicemail, then exploited a vulnerability in Cloudflare's use of Google's two-factor authentication system.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Once in control of Prince's email account, UGNazi was able to redirect the 4chan domain through Cloudflare's database.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] From September 2016 until February 2017, a Cloudflare bug nicknamed Cloudbleed leaked sensitive data, including passwords and authentication tokens, from customer websites by sending extra data in response to web requests.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] On November 18, 2025, Cloudflare suffered a major global outage that caused widespread 500 errors, slowing down many platforms, making them unreachable or completely down for users around the world.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Access to WARP, Cloudflare's VPN service, was also briefly disabled in London.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] During the outage, a spokesperson for Cloudflare said the company had seen a "spike in unusual traffic", causing some traffic passing through its network to experience errors.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] At 14:23 UTC, *The Guardian* reported that Cloudflare had released a fix.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] It also reported that maintenance was due at various locations, though this is not known to have caused the outages.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] At 14:42 UTC, Cloudflare informed users on its status page that the fix had been implemented and that it would take some time for remaining post-deployment issues to be fixed.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] A technical postmortem of the incident was released the day following the outage.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare attributed the outage to a change in the configuration of a database, which caused an invalid file to be sent to all servers on the network.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] On December 5, Cloudflare suffered another global outage, which began at 09:00 AM UTC.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] This was the second such outage in three weeks to affect Cloudflare's services.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In January 2026, security researchers disclosed a vulnerability in Cloudflare's Web application firewall (WAF) that allowed attackers to bypass security rules and access origin servers directly.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] The flaw existed in the handling of ACME challenge requests; the logic disabled WAF protections for requests targeting the `/.well-known/acme-challenge/` path without sufficiently verifying if the token matched an active validation attempt.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare patched the vulnerability in October 2025, stating that the issue was a logic flaw rather than a code execution vulnerability and that there was no evidence of exploitation.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare has established a content neutrality policy and opposes the policing of its customers on the basis of free speech unless said customers break the law.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] The company has faced criticism for not banning hate speech websites and websites allegedly connected to terrorism groups.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare has maintained that no law enforcement agency has asked the company to discontinue these services and it closely monitors its obligations under U.S. laws.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In 2022, a research paper by Stanford University found that Cloudflare was a prominent CDN provider, among several other providers, that are disproportionately responsible for serving misinformation websites.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare has come under pressure due to its services being utilized to access far-right content.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare provided DNS routing and DDoS protection for the white supremacist and neo-Nazi website *The Daily Stormer*.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In 2017, after previously refusing to take any action against the website, Cloudflare stopped providing its services to *The Daily Stormer* after an announcement on the website asserted that Cloudflare executives were privately supporting its ideology.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] As a self-described "free speech absolutist", Prince claimed he did not want to repeat the decision, and sought out protections for the company should they be faced with a similar situation in the future.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Prince further addressed the dangers of large companies deciding what is allowed to stay online, a concern shared by a number of civil liberties groups and privacy experts.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] The Electronic Frontier Foundation, a US digital rights group, said that services such as Cloudflare should not be deciding what speech is acceptable and that illegal content should be handled through the legal system.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In 2019, Cloudflare was criticized for providing services to the far-right discussion and imageboard 8chan.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] The message board has been linked to mass shootings in the United States and the Christchurch mosque shootings in New Zealand.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In addition, a number of news organizations including *The Washington Post* and *The Daily Dot* have reported on the existence of child pornography and child sexual abuse discussion boards.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] A Cloudflare representative said that the platform "does not host the referenced websites, cannot block websites, and is not in the business of hiding companies that host illegal content".
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare did not terminate service to 8chan until public and legal pressure mounted in the wake of the 2019 El Paso shooting, in which the associated manifesto was published to 8chan.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In an interview with *The Guardian* immediately after the shooting, CEO Matthew Prince defended Cloudflare's support of 8chan, saying that he had a "moral obligation" to keep 8chan online.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] On August 5, 2019, two days after Prince's interview with The Guardian, Cloudflare terminated service to 8chan.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare explained that 8chan "have proven themselves to be lawless and that lawlessness has caused multiple tragic deaths.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare provided DDoS mitigation and acted as a reverse proxy for Kiwi Farms.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] The site often engages in harassment and doxxing of targets and has been implicated in the suicides of at least three people.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Kiwi Farms also has a reputation for transphobic content, and its users have been accused of swatting vulnerable individuals.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Although Cloudflare was not the primary website host, it did perform critical services to keep Kiwi Farms on-line, both protecting the site from denial-of-service attacks and optimizing content delivery.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In 2022, a campaign was launched by transgender activist Clara Sorrenti, who has previously been targeted by the forum, to pressure Cloudflare into terminating service for Kiwi Farms.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare responded by issuing a statement on its abuse policies and saying it didn't want to set precedent for speech on the internet with its "extraordinary" decision.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] The company also released a blog post and likened its services to that of a public utility, emphasizing that it does not believe in shutting down security services based on content it finds objectionable.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] They acknowledged that while it might be more popular to remove sites that the Cloudflare team finds offensive, it stood by its decision not to do so.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] The company also defended its decision by saying that it donated all earnings from anti-LGBTIQ+ sites to an organization that advocated for LGBTIQ+ rights.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] On September 3, 2022, Cloudflare blocked Kiwi Farms, citing urgent escalating rhetoric against targets of Kiwi Farms, stating that there is an "unprecedented emergency and immediate threat to human life".
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Switter was a social media network for the sex worker community, built by Australia-based company Assembly Four on Mastodon's open-source software, before Cloudflare dropped Switter as a client and ceased services in April 2018, citing terms of service violations.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] This occurred shortly after the passage of FOSTA/SESTA, a set of bills criminalizing websites that facilitate or support sex trafficking in 2018.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] SESTA weakened protections for Internet infrastructure companies and was criticized on free speech grounds due to concerns about disproportionate impact and disruptions to the lives of sex workers.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare said the move was "related to our attempts to understand FOSTA, which is a very bad law and [sets] a very dangerous precedent".
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Assembly Four said that "Given Cloudflare's previous stances of privacy and freedom, as well as fighting alongside the EFF, we had hoped they would take a stand against FOSTA/SESTA".
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In 2015, testimony to the United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs, it was reported that two of the top three online chat forums and nearly forty other web sites belonging to the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant (ISIL) were guarded by Cloudflare.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare has been cited in reports by The Spamhaus Project, an international spam tracking organization, for the high numbers of cybercriminal botnet operations hosted by Cloudflare.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] An October 2015 report found that Cloudflare provisioned 40% of the SSL certificates used by typosquatting phishing sites, which use deceptive domain names resembling those of banks and payment processors to compromise Internet users' banking and other transactions.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare has been criticized for having a conflict of interest by providing DDoS protection to both the operators and victims of "stresser" services.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In 2018, Cloudflare was identified by the European Union's Counterfeit and Piracy Watch List as a "notorious market" which engages in, facilitates, or benefits from counterfeiting and piracy.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] The report noted that Cloudflare hides and anonymizes the operators of 40% of the world's pirate sites, and 62% of the 500 largest such sites, and "does not follow due diligence when opening accounts for websites to prevent illegal sites from using its services".
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In 2020, an Italian court ruled Cloudflare had to block current and future domain names and IP addresses of the pirate IPTV service "IPTV THE BEST" for infringing on Lega Serie A intellectual property.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] At the time, Cloudflare was already blocking 22 domain names in Italy.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Following the December 2024 court ruling, the Spanish LaLiga requested that telephone operators block Cloudflare's IP address ranges in February 2025.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare hosted websites that illegally broadcast soccer matches.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] As a result, the pirate platform DuckVision was shut down before the derby between Real Madrid and Atlético Madrid.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] The platform had 200,000 users and was backed by Cloudflare.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] The blocks affected major legitimate websites, including X, Vimeo, Steam, GitHub, and the Royal Spanish Academy.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare CEO Matthew Prince responded that the company decided to remain providing services to Russian people to counter Russia's attempts to raise a 'digital iron curtain'.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] Cloudflare's Project Galileo, launched in 2014, offers DDoS protection to NGOs for free.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In 2022, they extended free protection to Ukrainian government and telecoms.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] In 2022, Japanese publishers Shueisha, Kodansha, Shogakukan, and Kadokawa Shoten filed a copyright lawsuit against Cloudflare, alleging that the service was distributing data to manga piracy sites and sought an injunction and ¥460 million (US$4 million) in damages.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] On November 19, 2025, a judge ruled in favor of the publishers.
[src:cloudflare-workers/cloudflare] While the ruling recognized approximately ¥3.6 billion (US$24 million) in damages, Cloudflare was ordered to pay a total amount of ¥500 million (US$3.6 million), as the publishers claimed that Cloudflare was only partially responsible for the damages.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] The term began being used in the 1990s to describe content delivery networks—these were used to deliver website and video content from servers located near users.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] In the early 2000s, these systems expanded their scope to hosting other applications, leading to early edge computing services.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] These services could do things like find dealers, manage shopping carts, gather real-time data, and place ads.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] The Internet of things (IoT), where devices are connected to the Internet, is often linked with edge computing.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] Edge computing involves running computer programs that deliver quick responses close to where requests are made.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] Karim Arabi, during an IEEE DAC 2014 keynote and later at an MIT MTL Seminar in 2015, described edge computing as computing that occurs outside the cloud, at the network's edge, particularly for applications needing immediate data processing.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] Edge computing is often equated with fog computing, particularly in smaller setups.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] However, in larger deployments, such as smart cities, fog computing serves as a distinct layer between edge computing and cloud computing, with each layer having its own responsibilities.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] "The State of the Edge" report explains that edge computing focuses on servers located close to the end-users.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] Alex Reznik, Chair of the ETSI MEC ISG standards committee, defines 'edge' loosely as anything that's not a traditional data center.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] In cloud gaming, edge nodes, known as "gamelets", are typically within one or two network hops from the client, ensuring quick response times for real-time games.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] Edge computing might use virtualization technology to simplify deploying and managing various applications on edge servers.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] In 2018, the world's data was expected to grow 61 percent to 175 zettabytes by 2025.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] According to research firm Gartner, around 10 percent of enterprise-generated data is created and processed outside a traditional centralized data center or cloud.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] By 2025, the firm predicts that this figure will reach 75 percent.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] The increase in IoT devices at the edge of the network is producing a massive amount of data — storing and using all that data in cloud data centers pushes network bandwidth requirements to the limit.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] Despite the improvements in network technology, data centers cannot guarantee acceptable transfer rates and response times, which often is a critical requirement for many applications.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] Furthermore, devices at the edge constantly consume data coming from the cloud, forcing companies to decentralize data storage and service provisioning, leveraging physical proximity to the end user.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] In a similar way, the aim of edge computing is to move the computation away from data centers towards the edge of the network, exploiting smart objects, mobile phones, or network gateways to perform tasks and provide services on behalf of the cloud.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] By moving services to the edge, it is possible to provide content caching, service delivery, persistent data storage, and IoT management resulting in better response times and transfer rates.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] At the same time, distributing the logic to different network nodes introduces new issues and challenges.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] The distributed nature of this paradigm introduces a shift in security schemes used in cloud computing.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] In edge computing, data may travel between different distributed nodes connected via the internet, and thus requires special encryption mechanisms independent of the cloud.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] This approach minimizes latency, reduces bandwidth consumption, and enhances real-time responsiveness for applications.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] Edge nodes may also be resource-constrained devices, limiting the choice in terms of security methods.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] Moreover, a shift from centralized top-down infrastructure to a decentralized trust model is required.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] On the other hand, by keeping and processing data at the edge, it is possible to increase privacy by minimizing the transmission of sensitive information to the cloud.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] Furthermore, the ownership of collected data shifts from service providers to end-users.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] Scalability in a distributed network must face different issues.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] First, it must take into account the heterogeneity of the devices, having different performance and energy constraints, the highly dynamic condition, and the reliability of the connections compared to more robust infrastructure of cloud data centers.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] Moreover, security requirements may introduce further latency in the communication between nodes, which may slow down the scaling process.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] The state-of-the-art scheduling technique can increase the effective utilization of edge resources and scales the edge server by assigning minimum edge resources to each offloaded task.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] Management of failovers is crucial in order to keep a service alive.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] If a single node goes down and is unreachable, users should still be able to access a service without interruptions.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] Moreover, edge computing systems must provide actions to recover from a failure and alert the user about the incident.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] To this aim, each device must maintain the network topology of the entire distributed system, so that detection of errors and recovery become easily applicable.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] Other factors that may influence this aspect are the connection technologies in use, which may provide different levels of reliability, and the accuracy of the data produced at the edge that could be unreliable due to particular environment conditions.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] As an example, an edge computing device, such as a voice assistant, may continue to provide service to local users even during cloud service or internet outages.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] Edge computing brings analytical computational resources close to the end users and therefore can increase the responsiveness and throughput of applications.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] A well-designed edge platform would significantly outperform a traditional cloud-based system.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] Some applications rely on short response times, making edge computing a significantly more feasible option than cloud computing.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] Examples range from IoT to autonomous driving, anything health or human / public safety relevant, or involving human perception such as facial recognition, which typically takes a human between 370-620 ms to perform.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] Edge computing is more likely to be able to mimic the same perception speed as humans, which is useful in applications such as augmented reality, where the headset should preferably recognize who a person is at the same time as the wearer does.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] Due to the nearness of the analytical resources to the end users, sophisticated analytical tools and artificial intelligence tools can run on the edge of the system.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] This placement at the edge helps to increase operational efficiency and is responsible for many advantages to the system.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] In distributed AI systems on the edge, data compression is increasingly recognized as a foundational design layer to mitigate bandwidth constraints caused by the exchange of large models and high-resolution sensor streams.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] By using servers located on a local edge network to perform those computations, the video files only need to be transmitted in the local network.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] Avoiding transmission over the internet results in significant bandwidth savings and therefore increases efficiency.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] If the recognition is performed locally, it is possible to send the recognized text to the cloud rather than audio recordings, significantly reducing the amount of required bandwidth.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] Edge application services reduce the volumes of data that must be moved, the consequent traffic, and the distance that data must travel.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] That provides lower latency and reduces transmission costs.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] Computation offloading for real-time applications, such as facial recognition algorithms, showed considerable improvements in response times, as demonstrated in early research.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] Further research showed that using resource-rich machines called cloudlets or micro data centers near mobile users, which offer services typically found in the cloud, provided improvements in execution time when some of the tasks are offloaded to the edge node.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] On the other hand, offloading every task may result in a slowdown due to transfer times between device and nodes, so depending on the workload, an optimal configuration can be defined.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] An IoT-based power grid system enables communication of electricity and data to monitor and control the power grid, which makes energy management more efficient.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] Other notable applications include connected cars, self-driving cars, smart cities, Industry 4.0, home automation, missiles,, satellite systems , as well as frameworks such as MediaPipe.
[src:cloudflare-workers/edge-computing] The growing field of **edge artificial intelligence** (edge AI or edge intelligence, sometimes referred to as "local AI" or "on-device AI") implements artificial intelligence in an edge computing environment, on the device or close to where data is collected.
[src:cloudflare-workers/javascript-engine] The first JavaScript engines were interpreters of the source code, but modern engines use just-in-time compilation to improve performance.
[src:cloudflare-workers/javascript-engine] JavaScript engines are typically developed by web browser vendors, and every major browser includes one.
[src:cloudflare-workers/javascript-engine] In a browser, the JavaScript engine runs in concert with the rendering engine via the Document Object Model and Web IDL bindings.
[src:cloudflare-workers/javascript-engine] However, the use of JavaScript engines is not limited to browsers; For example, the V8 engine is a core component of the Node.js runtime system.
[src:cloudflare-workers/javascript-engine] They are also called ECMAScript engines, after the official name of the specification.
[src:cloudflare-workers/javascript-engine] With the advent of WebAssembly, some engines can also execute this code in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:cloudflare-workers/javascript-engine] The first JavaScript engine was created by Brendan Eich in 1995 for the Netscape Navigator web browser.
[src:cloudflare-workers/javascript-engine] It was a rudimentary interpreter for the nascent language Eich invented.
[src:cloudflare-workers/javascript-engine] Google debuted its Chrome browser in 2008, introducing the V8 JavaScript engine that was at the time much faster than its competition.
[src:cloudflare-workers/javascript-engine] This sparked a race between browser vendors to deliver ever-faster JavaScript engines.
[src:cloudflare-workers/javascript-engine] The key innovations around this era were switching from basic tree-walking interpreters to stack- and register-based bytecode VM interpreters, just-in-time compilation (JIT), inline caching (hidden classes) and generational GC.
[src:cloudflare-workers/javascript-engine] Apple released the JIT-enabled Nitro engine in June 2008 for its Safari browser, which had 30% better performance than its predecessor.
[src:cloudflare-workers/javascript-engine] Mozilla followed suit in August 2008 with TraceMonkey, the first JIT compiler for SpiderMonkey engine, released in Firefox 3.1.
[src:cloudflare-workers/javascript-engine] Opera joined the performance race with their register-bytecode based and JIT-enabled Carakan engine, 2009 and released in April 2010.
[src:cloudflare-workers/javascript-engine] Microsoft's first JIT-enabled Chakra engine, in development since 2008, debuted as part of Internet Explorer 9 in 2011.
[src:cloudflare-workers/javascript-engine] Its major rewrite appeared in Microsoft Edge Legacy in 2015 and open-sourced as ChakraCore in 2016.
[src:cloudflare-workers/javascript-engine] Further performance gains in major JavaScript engines were later achieved with the introduction of multi-tiered JIT architectures.
[src:cloudflare-workers/javascript-engine] Progressively advanced JIT compilers are used to optimize hotspots in user code, with each next tier delivering ever more performant native code at the cost of slower compile time.
[src:cloudflare-workers/javascript-engine] Chrome was the first to implement it in V8 in 2010 with the introduction of Crankshaft, a 2-tiered JIT compiler.
[src:cloudflare-workers/javascript-engine] By 2023, architecture of V8 evolved into 4 tiers: Ignition – register-based bytecode interpreter, Sparkplug – a fast non-optimizing JIT compiler, Maglev and TurboFan – slower optimizing JIT compilers.
[src:cloudflare-workers/javascript-engine] JavaScriptCore today has a similar 4-tier architecture, while Firefox's SpiderMonkey and ChakraCore have 3 tiers (interpreter and 2-tiered JIT).
[src:cloudflare-workers/javascript-engine] V8's influence expanded beyond browsers with the release of Node.js in 2009 and its package manager npm in 2010.
[src:cloudflare-workers/javascript-engine] As their popularity exploded, V8 also became the engine powering vast amounts of server-side JavaScript code.
[src:cloudflare-workers/javascript-engine] In 2013, Electron framework appeared that let developers create desktop apps with web technologies as well, using Chromium with V8 and Node.js under the hood.
[src:cloudflare-workers/javascript-engine] Eventually asm.js and NaCl (a competing Google's technology) evolved into WebAssembly standard in 2017, with all major engines adding support for it.
[src:cloudflare-workers/javascript-engine] The six-year gap between ECMAScript 5 (2009) and ES6 (2015) marked a major inflection point for JavaScript engine development.
[src:cloudflare-workers/javascript-engine] Whereas ES5 was a relatively compact language with straightforward basic implementation, ES6 introduced foundations of modern JavaScript, with substantially increased complexity, as well as an annual release cycle for new specification versions.
[src:cloudflare-workers/javascript-engine] This put the focus not only on performance optimization, but also on keeping pace with the rapidly evolving standards (of both ECMAScript and wider web ecosystem) and led to a consolidation around engines that had the resources to do it.
[src:cloudflare-workers/javascript-engine] Many smaller projects did not end up fully implementing ES6 spec, and Opera and Microsoft both ceased developing their engines and adopted V8 in 2013 and 2021.
[src:cloudflare-workers/javascript-engine] Nashorn engine was dropped from OpenJDK over a similar concern about ECMAScript's rapid development.
[src:cloudflare-workers/javascript-engine] These engines have been discontinued and are mostly interesting for the historical perspective.
[src:cloudflare-workers/javascript-engine] Some may still be in use today for legacy purposes (especially Microsoft's old engines that continue to ship with Windows).
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] Serverless computing does not eliminate complexity but shifts much of it from the operations team to the development team.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] However, this shift is not absolute, as operations teams continue to manage aspects such as identity and access management (IAM), networking, security policies, and cost optimization.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] Additionally, while breaking down applications into finer-grained components can increase management complexity, the relationship between granularity and management difficulty is not strictly linear.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] There is often an optimal level of modularization where the benefits outweigh the added management overhead.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] According to Yan Cui, serverless techniques should be adopted only when they help to deliver customer value faster.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] And while adopting, organizations should take small steps and de-risk along the way.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] Serverless applications are prone to fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] Monitoring and debugging serverless applications can present unique challenges due to their distributed, event-driven nature and proprietary environments.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] Traditional tools may fall short, making it difficult to track execution flows across services.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] However, modern solutions such as distributed tracing tools (e.g., AWS X-Ray, Datadog), centralized logging, and cloud-agnostic observability platforms are mitigating these challenges.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] Emerging technologies like OpenTelemetry, AI-powered anomaly detection, and serverless-specific frameworks are further improving visibility and root cause analysis.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] While challenges persist, advancements in monitoring and debugging tools are steadily addressing these limitations.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] According to OWASP, serverless applications are vulnerable to variations of traditional attacks, insecure code, and some serverless-specific attacks (like *denial of wallet*).
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] So, the risks have changed and attack prevention requires a shift in mindset.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] Serverless computing is provided as a third-party service.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] Applications and software that run in the serverless environment are by default locked to a specific cloud vendor.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] This issue is exacerbated in serverless computing, as with its increased level of abstraction, public vendors only allow customers to upload code to a FaaS platform without the authority to configure underlying environments.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] More importantly, when considering a more complex workflow that includes backend-as-a-service (BaaS), a BaaS offering can typically only natively trigger a FaaS offering from the same provider.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] This makes the workload migration in serverless computing virtually impossible.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] Therefore, considering how to design and deploy serverless workflows from a multi-cloud perspective could mitigate this.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] Serverless computing may not be ideal for certain high-performance computing (HPC) workloads due to resource limits often imposed by cloud providers, including maximum memory, CPU, and runtime restrictions.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] For workloads requiring sustained or predictable resource usage, bulk-provisioned servers can sometimes be more cost-effective than the pay-per-use model typical of serverless platforms.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] However, serverless computing is increasingly capable of supporting specific HPC workloads, particularly those that are highly parallelizable and event-driven, by leveraging its scalability and elasticity.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] The suitability of serverless computing for HPC continues to evolve with advancements in cloud technologies.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] The *grain of sand* anti-pattern refers to the creation of excessively small components (e.g., functions) within a system, often resulting in increased complexity, operational overhead, and performance inefficiencies.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] *Lambda pinball* is a related anti-pattern that can occur in serverless architectures when functions (e.g., AWS Lambda, Azure functions) excessively invoke each other in fragmented chains, leading to latency, debugging and testing challenges, and reduced observability.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] These anti-patterns are associated with the formation of a distributed monolith.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] These anti-patterns are often addressed through the application of clear domain boundaries, which distinguish between public and published interfaces.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] Public interfaces are technically accessible interfaces, such as methods, classes, API endpoints, or triggers, but they do not come with formal stability guarantees.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] In contrast, published interfaces involve an explicit stability contract, including formal versioning, thorough documentation, a defined deprecation policy, and often support for backward compatibility.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] Published interfaces may also require maintaining multiple versions simultaneously and adhering to formal deprecation processes when breaking changes are introduced.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] Fragmented chains of function calls are often observed in systems where serverless components (functions) interact with other resources in complex patterns, sometimes described as spaghetti architecture or a distributed monolith.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] In contrast, systems exhibiting clearer boundaries typically organize serverless components into cohesive groups, where internal public interfaces manage inter-component communication, and published interfaces define communication across group boundaries.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] This distinction highlights differences in stability guarantees and maintenance commitments, contributing to reduced dependency complexity.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] Additionally, patterns associated with excessive serverless function chaining are sometimes addressed through architectural strategies that emphasize native service integrations instead of individual functions, a concept referred to as the functionless mindset.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] However, this approach is noted to involve a steeper learning curve, and integration limitations may vary even within the same cloud vendor ecosystem.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] Reporting on serverless databases presents challenges, as retrieving data for a reporting service can either break the bounded contexts, reduce the timeliness of the data, or do both.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] This applies regardless of whether data is pulled directly from databases, retrieved via HTTP, or collected in batches.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] Mark Richards refers to this as the *reach-in reporting* anti-pattern.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] A possible alternative to this approach is for databases to asynchronously push the necessary data to the reporting service instead of the reporting service pulling it.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] While this method requires a separate contract between services and the reporting service and can be complex to implement, it helps preserve bounded contexts while maintaining a high level of data timeliness.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] Adopting DevSecOps practices can help improve the use and security of serverless technologies.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] In serverless applications, the distinction between infrastructure and business logic is often blurred, with applications typically distributed across multiple services.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] To maximize the effectiveness of testing, integration testing is emphasized for serverless applications.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] Additionally, to facilitate debugging and implementation, orchestration is used within the bounded context, while choreography is employed between different bounded contexts.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] Ephemeral resources are typically kept together to maintain high cohesion.
[src:cloudflare-workers/serverless-computing] However, shared resources with long spin-up times, such as AWS RDS clusters and landing zones, are often managed in separate repositories, deployment pipeline, and stacks.
[src:cloudflare-workers/v8-javascript-engine] Google created V8 for its Chrome browser, so V8's first release coincided with Chrome's first release in 2008.
[src:cloudflare-workers/v8-javascript-engine] It was named after the V8 engine, and its lead developer was Lars Bak.
[src:cloudflare-workers/v8-javascript-engine] For several years, Chrome was faster than other browsers at executing JavaScript.
[src:cloudflare-workers/v8-javascript-engine] The V8 assembler is based on the Strongtalk assembler.
[src:cloudflare-workers/v8-javascript-engine] On 7 December 2010, a new compiling infrastructure named Crankshaft was released, with speed improvements.
[src:cloudflare-workers/v8-javascript-engine] In version 41 of Chrome in 2015, project TurboFan was added to provide more performance improvements with previously challenging workloads such as asm.js.
[src:cloudflare-workers/v8-javascript-engine] Much of V8's development is strongly inspired by the Java HotSpot Virtual Machine developed by Sun Microsystems, with the newer execution pipelines being very similar to those of HotSpot's.
[src:cloudflare-workers/v8-javascript-engine] Support for the WebAssembly language began in 2015.
[src:cloudflare-workers/v8-javascript-engine] In 2016, the Ignition interpreter was added to V8 with the design goal of reducing the memory usage on small memory Android phones in comparison with TurboFan and Crankshaft.
[src:cloudflare-workers/v8-javascript-engine] Ignition is a register based machine and shares a similar (albeit not the exact same) design to the templating interpreter utilized by HotSpot.
[src:cloudflare-workers/v8-javascript-engine] In 2017, V8 shipped a brand-new compiler pipeline, consisting of Ignition (the interpreter) and TurboFan (the optimizing compiler).
[src:cloudflare-workers/v8-javascript-engine] Starting with V8 version 5.9, Full-codegen (the early baseline compiler) and Crankshaft are no longer used in V8 for JavaScript execution, since the team believed they were no longer able to keep pace with new JavaScript language features and the optimizations those features required.
[src:cloudflare-workers/v8-javascript-engine] In 2021, a new tiered compilation pipeline was introduced with the release of the SparkPlug compiler, which supplements the existing TurboFan compiler within V8, in a direct parallel to the profiling C1 Compiler used by HotSpot.
[src:cloudflare-workers/v8-javascript-engine] V8 first generates an abstract syntax tree with its own parser.
[src:cloudflare-workers/v8-javascript-engine] Then, Ignition generates bytecode from this syntax tree using the internal V8 bytecode format.
[src:cloudflare-workers/v8-javascript-engine] TurboFan compiles this bytecode into machine code.
[src:cloudflare-workers/v8-javascript-engine] In other words, V8 compiles ECMAScript directly to native machine code using just-in-time compilation before executing it.
[src:cloudflare-workers/v8-javascript-engine] The compiled code is additionally optimized (and re-optimized) dynamically at runtime, based on heuristics of the code's execution profile.
[src:cloudflare-workers/v8-javascript-engine] Optimization techniques used include inlining, elision of expensive runtime properties, and inline caching.
[src:cloudflare-workers/v8-javascript-engine] The garbage collector is a generational incremental collector.
[src:cloudflare-workers/v8-javascript-engine] V8 can compile to x86, ARM or MIPS instruction set architectures in both their 32-bit and 64-bit editions; it has additionally been ported to PowerPC, and to IBM ESA/390 and z/Architecture, for use in servers.
[src:cloudflare-workers/v8-javascript-engine] V8 can be used in a browser or integrated into independent projects.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] The main goal of WebAssembly is to facilitate high-performance applications on web pages, but it is also designed to be usable in non-web environments.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] It is an open standard intended to support any language on any operating system, and in practice many of the most popular languages already have at least some level of support.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] Announced in 2015 (2015) and first released in March 2017 (2017-03), WebAssembly became a World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) recommendation on 5 December 2019 and it received the *Programming Languages Software Award* from the Association for Computing Machinery (ACM) SIGPLAN in 2021.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] The W3C maintains the standard with contributions from Mozilla, Microsoft, Google, Apple, Fastly, Intel, and Red Hat.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] The name "WebAssembly" is intended to suggest bringing assembly language programming to the World Wide Web, where it will be executed client-side, by the website-user's computer via the user's web browser.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] To accomplish this, WebAssembly must be much more hardware-independent than a true assembly language.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] WebAssembly was first announced in 2015, and the first demonstration was executing Unity's *Angry Bots* in Firefox, Google Chrome, and Microsoft Edge [Legacy].
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] The precursor technologies were asm.js from Mozilla and Google Native Client, and the initial implementation was based on the feature set of asm.js.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] In March 2017, the design of the minimum viable product (MVP) was declared to be finished and the preview phase ended.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] In late September 2017, Safari 11 was released with support.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] In February 2018, the WebAssembly Working Group published three public working drafts for the Core Specification, JavaScript Interface, and Web API.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] The MVP was focused on low-level languages such as C and C++, with the intent to add features useful for high-level languages in a future version.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] The WebAssembly 2.0 specification was finished in 2022 and became a W3C standard in December 2024.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] It adds many single instruction, multiple data (SIMD) related instructions and a new v128 datatype, with the ability for functions to return multiple values, mass memory initialize/copy instructions, and reference types, which are opaque pointers to objects outside of the linear memory.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] WebAssembly 3.0 was released in September 2025.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] New features include a 64-bit address space, multiple address spaces, exception handling, and garbage collected struct and array types.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] Support for garbage collection enables more efficient compiling for high-level languages, but WasmGC from WebAssembly 3.0 lacks the abilities needed by .NET runtime.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] While WebAssembly was initially designed to permit near-native code execution speed in the web browser, it has been considered valuable outside of such, in more generalized contexts.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] A WebAssembly runtime environment is a low-level virtual stack machine, akin to JVM or Flash VM; it can be embedded into any host application, and thus there have been created standalone WebAssembly runtime environments, including Wasmtime , WebAssembly Micro Runtime , Wasmer , WasmEdge and wazero .
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] In November 2017, Mozilla declared support "in all major browsers", after WebAssembly was enabled by default in Edge [Legacy] 16.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] This support also includes mobile web browsers for iOS and Android.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] As of March 2024, 99% of tracked web browsers support WebAssembly (version 1.0), more than for its predecessor asm.js.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] For some extensions, from the 2.0 draft standard, support may be lower, but still more than 90% of web browsers may already support, e.g. the reference types extension.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] Non-browser WebAssembly runtimes include Wasmer, Wasmtime, WAMR, WAVM, wasm3, and others.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] These systems execute precompiled Wasm modules and often provide additional APIs for embedding WebAssembly in different environments.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] Use cases for wasm outside the browser include plug-in interfaces and lightweight virtualization.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] WebAssembly implementations generally use either ahead-of-time (AOT) or just-in-time (JIT) compiling, though some may also use an interpreter.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] While the first implementations appeared in web browsers, there are now many non-browser implementations for general-purpose use.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] Because WebAssembly executables are precompiled, a variety of programming languages can target Wasm.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] Compiling is done either through direct output to Wasm or via intermediate virtual machines implemented in Wasm.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] As of 2021, around 40 programming languages support WebAssembly as a compiling target.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] Web browsers prevent WebAssembly code from directly manipulating the Document Object Model.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] Wasm code must defer to JavaScript for this.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] In an October 2023 survey of developers, less than half of the 303 participants were satisfied with the state of WebAssembly.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] A large majority cited the need for improvement in four areas: § WASI, debugging support, integration with JavaScript and browser APIs, and build tooling.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] All major browsers allow WebAssembly if `Content-Security-Policy` is not specified, or if the value `unsafe-eval` is used, but behave differently otherwise; Chrome *requires* `unsafe-eval`, though a worker thread can be a workaround.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] In June 2018, a security researcher presented the possibility of using WebAssembly to circumvent browser mitigations for Spectre and Meltdown security vulnerabilities once support for threads with shared memory is added.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] Due to this concern, WebAssembly developers put the feature on hold.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] However, in order to explore these future language extensions, Google Chrome added experimental support for the WebAssembly thread proposal in October 2018.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] WebAssembly has been criticized for allowing greater ease of hiding the evidence for malware writers, scammers and phishing attackers; WebAssembly is present on the user's machine only in its compiled form, which "[makes malware] detection difficult".
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] Speed and the easy ability to conceal in WebAssembly have led to its use in hidden crypto mining within the website visitor's device.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] An April 2021 study from Universität Stuttgart found that since then crypto mining has been marginalized, falling to below 1% of all WebAssembly modules gathered from a wide range of sources, also including the Alexa top 1 million websites.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] As WebAssembly supports only structured control flow, it is amenable toward security verification techniques including symbolic execution.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] In 2019, a group of researchers from the University of Massachusetts Amherst presented a comprehensive analysis of WebAssembly's performance compared to native code.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] The paper identified several reasons for this performance difference, including missing optimizations, code generation issues in WebAssembly compilers, and inherent limits of the WebAssembly platform.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] In 2022, it was determined by researchers that a Wasm program runs at about 120% of (or 20% faster than) the speed of a comparable JavaScript program.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] Those findings align with the experience of a startup company named "Zaplib", whose founders summarized in a blog that it was shutting down due to lack of performance in WebAssembly.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] Their goal had been to significantly increase the performance of existing web apps by incrementally porting them to Rust/Wasm; however, porting a customer's simulator from JavaScript yielded only a 5% improvement in performance.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] Benchmarking has revealed several other pain-points for WebAssembly, such as poor performance because of no direct access to the DOM, a problem which is being addressed.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] WebAssembly System Interface (WASI) is a simple interface (application binary interface (ABI) and application programming interface (API)) designed by Mozilla, which is intended to be portable to any platform.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] It provides features similar to the Portable Operating System Interface (POSIX), such as file input/output (I/O) constrained by capability-based security.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] WASI is influenced by CloudABI and Capsicum.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] Solomon Hykes, a co-founder of Docker, wrote in 2019, "If WASM+WASI existed in 2008, we wouldn't have needed to create Docker.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] WASI 0.1 provides a few POSIX-like APIs such as file I/O, reading environment variables, and random-number generation, but has very little support for networking.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] WASI 0.2 is redesigned based on the WebAssembly Component Model.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] WASI 0.3 will add support for async functions; the host translates between blocking and async function calls, so an exported function that blocks may be called as an asynchronous function, and vice-versa.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] Starting in 0.2, WASI is defined in terms of the component model.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] Interfaces in the component model are specified in an IDL called WIT (WebAssembly Interface Types).
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] While core wasm only supports integer and floating-point numbers, interfaces in WIT can express types such as strings, lists, and user-defined record and variant types, and are language-agnostic.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] Components cannot access each other's memory, and so interact only via imported and exported functions.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] The component model is designed around composition: two components can be composed into a single component when the exports of one component match another's imports, allowing any interface to be virtualized.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] Interfaces in WIT are grouped together into a "world".
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] WASI 0.2 defines a CLI world similar to the POSIX-like API of WASI 0.1, and an HTTP proxy world for web servers.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] The component model is not currently supported by browsers.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] The general standard provides core specifications for the JavaScript API and details on embedding.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] Wasm code (binary code, i.e. bytecode) is intended to be run on a portable virtual stack machine (VM).
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] The VM is designed to be faster to parse and execute than JavaScript and to have compact code representation.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] Any external functionality (like syscalls) that may be expected by Wasm binary code is not stipulated by the standard; instead, the standard specifies how the host environment can provide such an interface via a "module".
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] A Wasm program is designed as a separate module containing collections of various Wasm-defined values and program type definitions.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] These are provided in either binary or textual format (see below) that have a common structure.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] Such a module may provide a start function that is executed upon instantiation of a wasm binary.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] The list of instruction types includes those for standard memory load/store, numeric, parametric, control flow, and Wasm-specific variables.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] The number of opcodes used in the original standard (§ MVP) was a bit fewer than 200 of the 256 possible opcodes.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] Subsequent versions of WebAssembly pushed the number of opcodes a bit over 200.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] The WebAssembly SIMD proposal (for parallel processing) introduces an alternate opcode prefix (0xfd) for 128-bit wide SIMD instructions; the concatenation of the SIMD prefix, plus an opcode that is valid after the SIMD prefix, forms each SIMD opcode.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] These SIMD opcodes are both portable and intended to map directly to native instruction sets like x86-64 and ARM.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] In contrast, SIMD instructions are not directly supported by Java's JVM or .NET's CIL; however, both do have some APIs for parallel processing, which provide SIMD speedups.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] A newer set of "relaxed SIMD" instructions allow for a limited amount of implementation-defined behavior to improve performance.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] In March 2017, the WebAssembly Community Group reached consensus on the initial ("MVP") binary format, JavaScript API, and reference interpreter.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] It defines a WebAssembly binary format (`.wasm`), which is designed to be used by computers, not humans, and a text format that is human-readable (`.wat`), resembling a cross between S-expressions and traditional assembly languages.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] The binary format is straightforward and designed to allow streaming compiling, so compiling can begin before the module is finished downloading, and to allow functions to be compiled in parallel.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] All integer constants are encoded using a space-efficient, variable-length LEB128 encoding.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] The WebAssembly text format is more canonically written in a folded format using S-expressions.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] For instructions and expressions, this format is purely syntactic sugar and has no behavioral differences with the linear format.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] A module is implicitly generated by the compiler.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] The function is referenced by an entry of the type table in the binary, hence a type section and the `type` emitted by the decompiler.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] The compiler and decompiler can be accessed online.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] Data in memory is stored in a large, growable array of bytes termed a *linear memory*.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] Linear memory is separate from the wasm module's call stack and code and the engine's memory.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] This allows running wasm code in the same process as the JavaScript virtual machine it's embedded in without violating memory safety.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] A module contains a list of global variables separate from linear memory, which may be mutable or immutable.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] Functions declare a list of local variables.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] A function's parameters are also local variables.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] Instructions operate on a stack of values.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] The stack layout is fixed (branches must push and pop the same number of operands), so wasm engines can compile the stack away, producing efficient machine code operations on registers, rather than managing a stack at runtime.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] A stack machine architecture was chosen as it can have higher code density than a register machine.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] Unlike typical assembly languages, wasm only uses structured control flow similar to high-level programming languages.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] The intentional lack of support for jump instructions makes it simple to validate and compile wasm code in a single pass, and makes it easier to read code disassembled into the text format.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] Blocks are delimited with the `block`, `loop`, and `if`/`else` constructs.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] Branch instructions contain a label that identifies the depth of a block it is nested in: `br 0` will branch to the block the instruction is contained in, `br 1` will branch to the block that block is contained in, and so on.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] Branches to a `block` or `if` jump to the end of the block like a break statement, while branches to a `loop` jump back to the *beginning* of the loop, similar to a continue statement.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] The `br_table` instruction takes an input index and jumps to a target from a list of labels.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] A C-style switch statement can be expressed with a `br_table` inside a series of nested blocks.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] Compilers targeting wasm convert unstructured control flow into high-level loops using Emscripten's Relooper algorithm, originally designed to target JavaScript.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] Function declarations are listed in a separate section before the section containing the function bodies.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] Function pointers are emulated using an index into the global functions table, since code is not inside the linear memory.
[src:cloudflare-workers/webassembly] Functions can also be imported and exported, providing the foreign function interface to communicate with JavaScript or other embedders.
